The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will need to be provided.
Conditions will need to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to serve its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The longer-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be issues to come.
Some will say that the fatal error was to have allowed Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was nevertheless already obvious that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its trade unions were already pushing for Greek salaries to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction do not confine themselves to Greece.
Spain, with an unemployment rate of 20% and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as a mirror of its own future.
And if that is not the case, the markets take care of it.
Portugal and Italy fare a bit better.
Ces pays, tout comme la Grèce, doivent faire face à de fortes réductions de budget.
Comme la Grèce, ils ne peuvent pas procéder à une dévaluation de leur monnaie pour encourager les exportations.
Comme la Grèce, ils doivent faire face à une profonde récession.
Comme la Grèce, ils seront tentés de faire appel à l’aide.
Tout cela pose une seule question : la véritable erreur n’était-elle pas d’avoir créé l’euro ?
In the measure where I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you would have the right to ask me: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, the fact of creating the euro has not been an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway down the road to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well pass this one off as a stroll in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own mechanism for emergency funding.
Today, the members of the Union can only provide aid to Greece by overriding regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates uncertainty.
When European leaders offer aid, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems stem from the Lisbon Treaty, then it must be amended.
Furthermore, aid should not be granted under certain conditions alone but should be accompanied by a temporary oversight of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
The history shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries that will be subjected to such measures will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
This is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily placed its budget under the control of an expert specially appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, they wouldn't find it so bothersome.
The expert would not be of California origin, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the California state as well as the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, where orders from this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
The Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they first and foremost consider themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties but also closer political links.
Those who have a robust emergency aid mechanism will actually have to account for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they know very well who will be responsible.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles political integration in Europe.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not obligated to account for its actions but which today has adopted a monetary policy that is too aggressive, thus exacerbating the critical situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The huge current account surpluses of Germany further worsen their situation.
In addition, her fiscal stimulus measures were not sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has benefited significantly from the creation of the euro.
She should return the favor.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as the political integration necessary to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Is she not in the best position to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe towards a more complete political integration.
We can only hope so.
